 \section{Configurable Colour Rendition and Band-Dependent Scattering}

  The current Earth renderer now supports two related but distinct colour-rendering modes. In the legacy mode, the visible appearance is
  controlled primarily through user-specified RGB triplets associated with land-cover classes, cloud, and ice. This mode is retained because
  it is fast, visually useful, and backward-compatible with earlier tuning work. In addition, a new \texttt{physical\_rgb} mode has been
  introduced. This newer mode is still deliberately simple, but it moves the model closer to an explicit visible-band reflectance formulation.
  In practical terms, the red, green, and blue channels are interpreted as approximate camera bands centred near 650\,nm, 550\,nm, and
  450\,nm, and the assigned class colours are treated as broadband reflectance anchors rather than purely display-oriented colours.

  The switch between these two modes is exposed directly in the Earth configuration via \texttt{earth\_color\_model = "legacy"} or
  \texttt{earth\_color\_model = "physical\_rgb"}. This is important scientifically because it allows experiments with different colour
  assumptions without breaking the previously tuned workflow. In the \texttt{physical\_rgb} mode, the MODIS IGBP land-surface classes are
  assigned a separate set of visible-band reflectance triplets. These may still be adjusted by the user, and this is intentional: the aim is
  not to freeze the surface model prematurely, but to make the colour assumptions explicit, inspectable, and reproducible.

  The same philosophy applies to cloud and ice. In legacy mode, cloud and ice colours are specified through \texttt{cloud\_rgb} and
  \texttt{ice\_rgb}. In the newer mode, the defaults are shifted toward more neutral solar-coloured reflectors via
  \texttt{physical\_cloud\_rgb} and \texttt{physical\_ice\_rgb}. This reflects the expectation that optically thick clouds and bright snow or
  ice should usually be much less chromatic than vegetated land, desert terrain, or ocean water. Because these quantities remain configuration
  parameters, the user can still explore alternative assumptions about cloud whiteness, sea-ice tint, or land-ice brightness when scientific
  or illustrative needs differ.

  The atmosphere is also wavelength-dependent, but at present it should still be regarded as semi-physical rather than fully derived from
  first principles. The model separates Rayleigh and aerosol optical depth, applies them independently in the red, green, and blue bands, and
  uses them both to attenuate surface radiance and to generate additive path radiance. Thus, the atmosphere is not merely a display tint: it
  contributes chromatic structure through per-band transmission and scattering. However, the governing parameters are still specified directly
  as \texttt{rayleigh\_tau\_rgb} and \texttt{aerosol\_tau\_rgb}, together with a Henyey--Greenstein asymmetry parameter \texttt{aerosol\_g},
  an overall strength factor, and a sky-colour term. The result is therefore physically motivated and wavelength-aware, but not yet a full
  pressure-, composition-, and wavelength-law-derived atmospheric solver.

  This separation of concerns is useful. Surface class colour, cloud and ice reflectance, ocean appearance, and atmospheric scattering can now
  be adjusted independently and transparently. For exploratory Earth rendering, this is a substantial improvement over a single monolithic RGB
  tuning step. It allows the user to ask separate scientific questions such as whether a given colour trend arises from surface classes, from
  cloud neutralisation, from aerosol loading, or from Rayleigh-enhanced blue scattering at the limb. The current implementation is therefore
  best viewed as an intermediate stage between a purely illustrative RGB renderer and a more rigorously band-integrated Earth radiance model.


